    <Table CellSpacing="5">
      <TableRowGroup>
        <TableRow>
          <TableCell>
            <Paragraph FontSize="22"><Run>How to: Get the Current Application Object</Run>

            </Paragraph>

          </TableCell>

        </TableRow>

        <TableRow/>
      </TableRowGroup>

    </Table>

    <Paragraph>This example shows how to get a reference to the Application object instance for the current AppDomain. 
    </Paragraph>

    <Paragraph FontSize="22">Example
    </Paragraph>

    <Paragraph><Run FontWeight="Bold">Application</Run>
 is implemented as a singleton, which ensures that only one set of application-scope properties and resources, and other shared services, are available per <Run FontWeight="Bold">AppDomain</Run>
. Furthermore, only one instance of the <Run FontWeight="Bold">Application</Run>
 type can be created per <Run FontWeight="Bold">AppDomain</Run>
.
    </Paragraph>

    <Paragraph>The following example shows how to get a reference to the current <Run FontWeight="Bold">Application</Run>
 object instance from the Current property.
    </Paragraph>

    <Table CellSpacing="5">
      <TableRowGroup>
        <TableRow>
          <TableCell>
            <Paragraph FontSize="22"><Run>C# </Run>

            </Paragraph>

          </TableCell>

        </TableRow>

        <TableRow>
          <TableCell>
            <Paragraph xml:space="preserve" TextAlignment="Left" FontSize="8pt" FontFamily="Courier New"><Run>// Get a reference to the current Application object Application currentApplication = Application.Current; 
</Run>

            </Paragraph>

          </TableCell>

        </TableRow>

      </TableRowGroup>

    </Table>

